==English==
===Etymology===
Via French, from Turkish [[sipahi]], from Persian {{FAchar|[[سپاهي]]}} (sipāhī) ‘horseman, soldier’ (> English [[sepoy]]), from {{FAchar|[[سپاه]]}} (sipāh) ‘army’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'spɑ:hi:/

===Noun===
{{en-noun|spahi|spahis}}
# ''(historic)'' an Ottoman Turkish [[cavalryman]]
#:*'''2001''': ‘I hear that the great Sadiki Bey illustrated a copy of ''Strange Creatures'', commissioned by an Uzbek '''spahi''' cavalryman, for only forty gold pieces.’ — Orhan Pamuk, ''My Name Is Red'', tr. Erdağ M Göknar